@Cindy 

Yeah! ✊

In this puzzle, the generations are consecutive from Greatest through Alpha EXCEPT GEN-X. Puzzle fail! 

Even if one weren't so obviously biased as myself, it just feels like a cop-out. If "gen" is already used in a themer, find a different spangram! I felt similarly with the whales the other day: some themers are words that modify "whale", and others stand on their own. (You can't identify a whale by saying only RIGHT, but you can with ORCA...) Even moreso with the cocktails: since pretty much every word ever has probably been used in cocktail names, the theme set felt random, and thus weak...

I know, I set a high bar! Would really up the game satisfaction though, IMHO.

@Jane Wheelaghan 

At many events, appetizers and drinks are served in a separate location, outside of the main dining area, during what we call a cocktail hour.  These "hors d'oeuvres", meaning "outside of the (main) work", are not thought of as a course, since the guests are not even in the dining room yet.

Once in the dining room, the typical event has three courses:  salad (or sometimes, soup, but not both), main, and dessert.

@Steve L 
We will occasionally serve both a salad and soup course (in that order). Plated appetizers are more usual at restaurants and private dinner-parties, but I have worked some very fancy events where there was an appetizer course. Not to mention an "intermezzo"--usually sorbet--or an "amuse-bouche" (separate from the appetizer).

"What does Miss Manners think when sits down at a table setting with four forks, three knives, and five spoons? That Miss Manners will not rise from the table hungry."

@Bill 

